'''''Coprinopsis atramentaria''''', commonly known as the '''common ink cap''' or '''inky cap''', is an edible (but sometimes poisonous, when combined with alcohol) mushroom found in Europe and North America. Previously known as ''Coprinus atramentarius'', it is the second best known ink cap and previous member of the genus ''[[Coprinus]]'' after ''[[Coprinus comatus|C.&nbsp;comatus]]''. It is a widespread and common [[fungus]] found throughout the northern hemisphere. Clumps of mushrooms arise after rain from spring to autumn, commonly in urban and disturbed habitats such as [[land lot|vacant lots]] and lawns, as well as grassy areas. The grey-brown [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] is initially bell-shaped before opening, after which it flattens and disintegrates. The flesh is thin and the taste mild. It can be eaten but is [[poison]]ous when consumed with [[alcoholic beverage|alcohol]] – hence another common name, '''tippler's bane'''.

== Taxonomy ==

The common ink cap was first described by French naturalist [[Jean Baptiste François Pierre Bulliard|Pierre Bulliard]] in 1786 as ''Agaricus atramentarius'' before being placed in the large genus ''[[Coprinus]]'' in 1838 by [[Elias Magnus Fries]]. The [[specific name (botany)|specific epithet]] is derived from the [[Latin]] word ''atramentum'' "ink".<ref name=Nilper>{{cite book | author = Nilson S & Persson O | year = 1977 | title = Fungi of Northern Europe 1: Larger Fungi (Excluding Gill-Fungi) | publisher = Penguin|isbn=0-14-063005-8|page=72}}</ref>

The genus was formerly considered to be a large one with well over 100 species. However, [[Molecular phylogenetics|molecular analysis]] of DNA sequences showed that most species belonged in the family [[Psathyrellaceae]], distinct from the [[type species]] that belonged to the [[Agaricaceae]]. It was given its current binomial name in 2001 as a result, as this and other species were moved to the new genus ''[[Coprinopsis]]''.<ref name="Red01">{{cite journal|year=2001|title=''Coprinus'' Pers. and the disposition of ''Coprinus'' species ''sensu lato''.|journal=Taxon|volume=50|issue=1|pages=203–41|doi=10.2307/1224525|jstor=1224525|author1=Redhead, Scott A|author2=Vilgalys, Rytas|author3=Moncalvo, Jean-Marc|author4=Johnson, Jacqui|author5=Hopple, Jr. John S|publisher=International Association for Plant Taxonomy (IAPT)}}</ref>

The term "tippler's bane" is derived from its ability to create acute sensitivity to alcohol, similar to [[disulfiram]] (Antabuse).<ref name="arora86">{{cite book |last=Arora |first=David |year=1986 |title=Mushrooms demystified: a comprehensive guide to the fleshy fungi |edition=2nd |location=Berkeley |publisher=Ten Speed Press |isbn=0-89815-169-4 |pages=347–48 |authorlink=David Arora |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/mushroomsdemysti00aror_0 }}</ref> Other common names include common ink cap and inky cap. The black liquid that this mushroom releases after being picked was once used as ink.<ref>Hall, Ian; ''et al''. (August 1, 2003). ''Edible and Poisonous Mushrooms of the World''. Timber Press. Portland, Oregon. {{ISBN|978-0-88192-586-9}}. p. 198.</ref>

== Description ==
[[File:A group of common ink cap mushrooms.jpg|thumb|150px|left|A group of young common ink cap mushrooms]]
Measuring 3–7&nbsp;cm (1.2–2.8&nbsp;in) in diameter, the greyish or brownish-grey [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] is initially bell-shaped,  is furrowed, and later splits. The colour is more brownish in the centre of the cap, which later flattens before melting. The very crowded [[Lamella (mycology)|gills]] are free; they are whitish at first but rapidly turn black and easily deliquesce. The short [[stipe (mycology)|stipe]] measures 7–17&nbsp;cm (2.8–6.8&nbsp;in) high by 1.5&nbsp;cm in diameter, is grey in colour, and lacks a ring. The [[spore print]] is dark brown, and the almond-shaped [[basidiospore|spores]] measure 8–11 by 5–6 [[micrometre|μm]].<ref name=Phillips06>{{cite book | last = Phillips |first=Roger | year = 2006  | title = Mushrooms | publisher = Pan MacMillan | isbn = 0-330-44237-6|page= 258}}</ref> The [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] is thin and pale grey in colour.<ref name="arora86"/>

== Distribution and habitat ==

''Coprinopsis atramentaria'' occurs across the [[Northern Hemisphere]], including Europe, North America,<ref name="arora86"/> and Asia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grzyby.pl/coprinus-site-Kees-Uljee/species/atrament.htm|title=Coprinus atramentarius (Bull.: Fr.) Fr. - Epicrisis: 243. 1838.|last=Uljé |first=Kees|work=Coprinus (studies in coprinus)|accessdate=2009-07-31}}</ref> but has also been found in [[Australia]],<ref name=Fuh05>{{cite book |title=A Field Guide to Australian Fungi |author=Fuhrer B|year=2005|page=43|publisher=Bloomings Books|location=Melbourne|isbn=1-876473-51-7}}</ref> where it has been recorded from such urban locations as the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Sydney|Royal Botanic Gardens]] in [[Sydney]] and around [[Lake Torrens National Park|Lake Torrens]],<ref name="Clel76">{{cite book | author= Cleland JB | year =1976| title = Toadstools and mushrooms and other larger fungi of South Australia | publisher = South Australian Government Printer |page =159}}</ref> and also in South Africa.<ref>{{cite journal |title=South African fungi 10: New species, new records and some new observations |first1=Derek A. |last1=Reid |first2=Albert |last2=Eicker |year=1999 |pages=169–97 |journal=Mycotaxon |volume=73}}<!-- http://www.mycotaxon.com/vol/73.html --></ref>

Like many ink caps, it grows in tufts. It is commonly associated with buried wood and is found in grassland, meadows, disturbed ground, and open terrain from late spring to autumn.<ref name=Phillips06/> Fruiting bodies have been known to push their way up through [[asphalt]]<ref name=Fuh05/> and even tennis courts.{{sfn|Ramsbottom|1953|p=128}} It is also common in urban areas and appears in vacant lots,<ref name="arora86"/> and tufts of fungi can be quite large and fruit several times a year.<ref name="arora86"/> If dug up, the [[mycelium]] can often be found originating on buried dead wood.{{sfn|Ramsbottom|1953|p=196}}

== Toxicity ==
[[File:Coprine.svg|thumb|right|Chemical structure of coprine]]
Consuming ''Coprinopsis atramentaria'' within a few hours of alcohol results in a "[[disulfiram]] syndrome".{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=284}}<ref name=michelot1992>{{cite journal |last1=Michelot |first1=Didier |title=Poisoning by ''Coprinus atramentarius'' |journal=Natural Toxins |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=73–80 |year=1992 |pmid=1344910 |doi=10.1002/nt.2620010203 }}</ref> This interaction has only been known since the early part of the twentieth century. Symptoms include facial reddening, nausea, vomiting, malaise, agitation, palpitations and tingling in limbs, and arise five to ten minutes after consumption of alcohol.{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=288}} If no more alcohol is consumed, they will generally subside over two or three hours. Symptom severity is proportional to the amount of alcohol consumed, becoming evident when blood alcohol concentration reaches 5&nbsp;mg/dL, and prominent at concentrations of 50–100&nbsp;mg/dL.  Disulfiram has, however, been known to cause [[myocardial infarction]] (heart attack).<ref>{{EMedicine|article|817759|Disulfiramlike Mushroom Toxicity}}</ref> The symptoms can occur if even a small amount of alcohol is consumed up to three days after eating the mushrooms, although they are milder as more time passes.{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=289}} Rarely, a [[cardiac arrhythmia]], such as [[atrial fibrillation]] on top of [[supraventricular tachycardia]], may develop.{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=289}}

The fungus contains a cyclopropylglutamine compound called [[coprine]].{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=286}} Its active metabolite, 1-aminocyclopropanol, blocks the action of an enzyme, [[acetaldehyde dehydrogenase]], which breaks down [[acetaldehyde]] in the body.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Marchner |first1=H. |last2=Tottmar |first2=O. |title=A Comparative Study on the Effects of Disulfiram, Cyanamide and 1-Aminocyclopropanol on the Acetaldehyde Metabolism in Rats |journal=Acta Pharmacologica et Toxicologica |volume=43 |issue=3 |pages=219–32 |year=1978 |pmid=707135 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0773.1978.tb02258.x }}</ref> Acetaldehyde is an intermediate [[metabolite]] of [[ethanol]] and is responsible for most symptoms of a [[hangover]]; its effect on autonomic [[Adrenergic receptor#.CE.B2 receptors|β receptors]] is responsible for the [[vasomotor]] symptoms.{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=286}}

Treatment involves reassuring the patient that the often frightening symptoms will pass, rehydration (fluid replacement) for fluid loss from vomiting, and monitoring for [[cardiac arrhythmia]]s.{{sfn|Benjamin|1995|p=290}}

Large and prolonged doses of coprine were found to have gonadotoxic effects on rats and dogs in testing.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jönsson |first1=Monica |last2=Lindquist |first2=Nils Gunnar |last3=Plöen |first3=Leif |last4=Ekvärn |first4=Sven |last5=Kronevi |first5=Tony |title=Testicular lesions of coprine and benzcoprine |journal=Toxicology |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=89–100 |year=1979 |pmid=473235 |doi=10.1016/0300-483X(79)90035-0 }}</ref>

